Capcom, Clarion, Dr. Ci:Labo, Sojitz: Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   A n n a   K i t a n a k a
-- 
2011-06-08T08:58:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-08/capcom-clarion-dr-ci-labo-sojitz-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Japanese trading tomorrow. Stock
symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close. The information in each item was released after
markets shut, unless stated otherwise.  Capcom Co. (9697 JT): The Japanese maker of “Monster
Hunter” video games said it plans to spend up to 3 billion yen
($38 million) to buy back up to 1.5 million common shares
between June 9 and July 20. The shares climbed 0.5 percent to
1,715 yen.  Clarion Co. (6796 JT): The car audio equipment maker
forecast full-year net income of 800 million yen on a parent
basis, compared with a 280 million yen loss a year earlier. The
stock advanced 1.5 percent to 132 yen.  Dr. Ci:Labo Co. (4924 JT): The cosmetics maker plans to buy
back 7.12 percent of its outstanding shares for 6.54 billion
yen. The company will offer 327,000 yen a share. The stock
gained 2.2 percent to 350,500 yen.  Hitachi High-Technologies Corp. (8036)  (8036 JT): The trading
company forecasts full-year net income of 18 billion yen this
year, compared with 17.8 billion yen a year earlier. Shares
advanced 2.9 percent to 1,713 yen.  Nissan Motor Co. (7201 JT):  Japan ’s second-largest
automaker, handed its directors average pay that was more than
twice that of its rivals  Toyota Motor Corp. (7203)  (7203 JT) and Honda
Motor Co. (7267 JT) for the fiscal year ended in March. Nissan
slipped 0.5 percent to 778 yen. Toyota climbed 0.2 percent to
3,290 yen. Honda lost 1.3 percent to 2,980 yen.  Sojitz Corp. (2768)  (2768 JT),  Hitachi Ltd. (6501)  (6501 JT) and
Mitsubishi-Hitachi Metals Machinery Inc. (HITAZ JP): The
companies won an order from Tata Steel Ltd. to build a hot strip
mill in  India ’s Orissa state. Sojitz shares rose 1.4 percent to
144 yen. Hitachi climbed 0.2 percent to 463 yen.  Separately, Hitachi plans to open an auto parts factory
near the Czech town of Zatec,  Lidove Noviny  reported, citing
CzechInvest, the government agency for promoting investment.  Tokyo Electric Power Co. (9501 JT): Reactors No. 1 and 2 at
the Fukushima Dai-Ichi nuclear power station suffered
electricity outages, plunging their control rooms into darkness
and halting the injection of nitrogen gas into the No. 1 unit.
The utility said it continues to inject water to cool the
reactors using independent power sources. Shares dropped 7.4
percent to 200 yen.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anna Kitanaka in  Tokyo  at 
 akitanaka@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 